        "title": "About Hungary - Basics",
        "content": "**1.0 Let’s start with a common question! Where do Hungarians come from?**\n\nThe Hungarians are often confused with the ancient Hun people, but the two peoples are only related by blood. The ancient tribe of the Hungarians originated from the then Yugra region, which is the present-day Russian steppe and Kazakh/Mongol territory.\n\nThey were considered as Eurasian people and were different in religion from European peoples. They believed in several gods and their religious leaders were shamans. They were a warrior people and were not very different from the Vikings, which means they were pagans in the eyes of the Europeans. During their long migrations, they mixed with many peoples, mainly Turkic peoples.\n\n[IMAGE:hungarian_migration]\n\n**1.0.1 The Hungarian Language**\n\nTThe Hungarian language belongs to the Uralic language family and can be classified as a Finno-Ugric language. Since the country was under different powers for centuries throughout history, the language has changed a lot from the original and has become even more complex. Nowadays, Hungarian also contains words from Turkish, German and Slavic languages. There are some grammatical rules like the Turkish language, but we can thank this for the 150 years of occupation.\n\n**1.4 Hungary's Annexations**\n\nHungary is not in a very fortunate place due to its geographical location. In the middle of Europe, the country has often fallen victim to larger empires. First, in the 16th century, the Turks ruled over the Hungarians for 150 years, then the Habsburg for almost 200 years. In World War II, the Germans invaded the country. After that, in 1947, our country belonged to the Soviet Union for more than 40 years. The Hungarians tried to free themselves from slavery three times, but without success.\n\n**The Flag during the Austrian Occupation**\n\n[IMAGE:flag_austria]\n\n**The Flag during the Soviet Union times**\n\n[IMAGE:flag_soviet]\n\n**The Árpád King Family first Flag**\n\n[IMAGE:flag_arpad]\n\n**1.4.1 The Revolutions**\n\n Hungary, we distinguish three major wars of independence.\n\nThe first is the Rákóczi-style war of independence. (1703-1710)\n\nFerenс Rákóczi rebelled against the Habsburg’s and tried to prevent Hungary from falling into Austrian hands. At first, he wanted to make peace with the Habsburg kings and Transylvania would have been recognised as a permanent separate principality. But before the compromise, he turned against them and fought against the Austrians. His battles were extremely successful. But financially he could not last long alone. Since the Spanish and Austrian branches of the Habsburg were at war over the inheritance. Rákóczi could easily travel around the country proclaiming the revolution. However, the fighting could not continue because the English and French kings no longer supported Ferenc. Later, Rákóczi died in Turkey.\n\nOur second great revolution was also against the Austrians in 1848-49.\n\nThe country rebelled against oppression. The main reasons for the people were that the Hungarian culture, people, trade and language were also oppressed. Hungarian soldiers were always sent to station abroad, while in the country the Austrian soldiers kept the people in terror. In 1848 the revolution started from the capital and demanded 12 points from the Habsburg leaders. The Hungarian soldiers were ordered home and in the first year of the freedom struggle the Austrian army was expelled from the country. Unfortunately, in 1849 the Habsburg King Franz Joseph called on the Russian Tsar for help and the freedom fighters were crushed from both sides. In retaliation, all 12 of our generals and 1 colonel were executed.\n\nOur third and final revolution was in 1956\n\nThe Soviet Union's oppression was a huge burden on the Hungarian people. The forced industrialisation and centralised trade took a lot of money from the people. The people became so impoverished that it was a miracle if a family could eat bread every day. In 1956, Polish riots broke out against the Soviet Union and the Hungarian Brotherhood took solidarity with them. Hungarian university students organised peaceful demonstrations and demanded the withdrawal of Soviet troops from the country. The demonstrations on October 23rd were peaceful until the evening when the young people wanted to have the 12 points read. The ÁVH then took the university students' representatives prisoner on the radio and did not want to release them. The crowd outside then rioted and wanted to break into the radio. This led to the secret political police (ÁVH) shooting into the crowd, starting the revolution. In the following days, young people took up arms and began to drag away ÁVH members and hang or beat them. As a result, Soviet troops attacked the insurgents and took up violence not only in Budapest, but throughout the country. Hungarian youth (from the age of 12 to 65) occupied military barracks and took up arms to fight the Soviets. On October 25, the Hungarian Communist Party capitulated to Moscow and the fighting subsided. The demonstrators marched again without weapons to the Parliament and renewed their demand for the fall of the government. Unfortunately, the secret police demanded revenge and fired into the crowd from the buildings surrounding the Parliament. Thousands of people died that day, and it is remembered as BLOODY THURSDAY. After the protesters continued to fight, the Soviets were temporarily forced to withdraw their troops from Hungary. But a few days later, on October 30, they sent back a larger force. About 2,000 tanks and 30,000 soldiers. But let's be clear about the numbers: Hitler also needed 2,000 tanks to occupy Belgium, the Netherlands and half of France. The 20,000 Hungarian wounded were eventually sentenced to prison or death. The next time it was allowed to talk about this was during the change of regime in 1989.The cut-out Soviet flag that became a symbol of the revolutionn\n\n**The cut-out Soviet flag became a symbol of the revolution**\n\n[IMAGE:revolution_soviet_flag]\n\n**3.1 Hungary During the Second World War**\n\nIn World War II, Hungary fought alongside Germany to regain territory lost due to the unjustly concluded World War I peace treaties. Since the war did not go well economically for the Hungarian army, they wanted to stop after regaining Northern Transylvania, but Hitler did not allow this.\n\nHungary had to send soldiers against Russia, but there were not enough weapons and ammunition. After the Hungarian armies suffered a serious defeat at the Don in 1943. After that, Miklós Horthy tried several times to get out of the war, but without success. Nazi sympathisers in the country carried out a coup and handed over control to the Germans. The siege of the capital, however, was very bloody. Budapest was the most difficult for the Soviets to capture. The siege of the capital lasted more than 53 days. On average, they managed to capture other large cities in 20-30 days. Of the 53 days, there were more than 13 days of bombing.\n\nThe battle for the city lasted so long because the Hungarian troops tried to take advantage of all the natural features. There is a tunnel system of several kilometres under the castle and they used this to hide from the bombings and here they were able to easily hide the population, who were not so threatened by the carpet bombing.\n\n[IMAGE:ww2_bombed_square]\n\n**The Budapest Ghetto**\n\nUnfortunately, since the Hungarians were on the wrong side in World War II, they not only adopted the war theories, but also the ideology of racial discrimination. In November 1944, Ferenc Szállasi and his Arrow Cross militia took control of the country and played everything into the hands of the Nazis. On November 29, 1944, the Jewish district was established, where the Jews were separated from the community. The ghetto was there from the end of November until January 17, 1945. Even during its short operation, thousands of Jews died here. Soviet soldiers liquidated the ghetto area and freed the prisoners. Walking around the area, we can see memorial plaques on almost every corner.\n\n[IMAGE:budapest_ghetto]",
