        "content": "[IMAGE:Heros]\n\n**Hero Square**\n\nThese groups of statues were also made for the 1000th anniversary. The statues standing on the arch are Hungarian heroic kings who did something great in history. In the middle are the seven ancient tribal leaders. Álmos, Előd, Ond, Kond, Tas, Huba and Töhötöm. Above them, the archangel Gabriel holds the Hungarian holy crown in his hand.\n\n**Statues in the left-hand colonnade (from left to right)**\n\nSaint Stephen –The founding Father\n\nSaint László – The knight king who conquered Croatia\n\nKálmán Könyves – The Most Educated King of all, Legislator\n\nAndrás II – The Tamer of Nobles, Fought in Jerusalem\n\nBéla IV – The Rebuilder, The second Father of the country\nCharles Robert – The Founder of the Great Economy, The Hungarian Forint founder\n\nLajos the Great – The Conqueror and Unifying\n\n**Statues in the right-hand colonnade (from left to right)**\n\nJános Hunyadi – The Turkish Beater Governor\n\nKing Matthias – The Strong Handed, The Man of Justice, The Prince of Vienna\n\nIstván Bocskai – The Protector of Transylvania\n\nGábor Bethlen – The Brave Transylvnian King of Hungary, Turned against the Habsburg’s\n\nImre Thököly – The Kuruc Leader\n\nFerenc II Rákóczi – The Betrayed and The Last Prince of Transylvania\n\nLajos Kossuth – The Rebel, till his last breath he was fighting for Hungarian sovereignty.\n\n**The City Park**\n\n[IMAGE:Park]\n\nThe City Park the City Park was built in the mid-19th century for the well-being of the community and as a place to spend free time. After the park was completed, the capital's zoo and amusement park were built here. Later, the Petőfi Hall was also built here, which was an open-air stage and concerts or operettas were performed. It reached its current form around 2020 and has undergone many renovations. The Park also houses the House of Music Museum and the Capital Railway History Museum. The Museum of Fine Arts and the Museum of Graphic Arts are located at Heroes' Square. Behind it is the lake where visitors can go boating in summer and ice skating in winter. However, the biggest attraction of the park is the Széchenyi Bath. This spa is the most famous in the city and we can thank Count István Széchenyi for this, who bought the Turkish bath in the area and turned it into something extraordinary.\n\n**Vajdahunyad Castle**\n\n[IMAGE:Vajd]\n\nThe building was built as a copy of the Vajdahunyad Castle of the Hunyadi family in 1896 for the 1000th anniversary. It should be noted that the building was rebuilt twice. The first building was built of wood due to a tight deadline. In 1899, it was demolished because it was in danger of collapsing. Public opinion protested the demolition, and under pressure, what we call the second building was rebuilt. The second castle was rebuilt in 1908 and has since housed the Hungarian Agricultural Museum. The building was built in Romanesque, Gothic and Renaissance-Baroque styles.\n\n**The Opera House**\n\n[IMAGE:Opera]\n\nOpera House the National Opera House was built in 1837. It was the first Hungarian-language theatre where performances were held in Hungarian. Since the Oprea quickly outgrew itself, it was renovated in 1884, giving it its current appearance. To this day, it is the only theatre where opera and ballet performances are performed. The building escaped with minor damage during World War II. This opera house has the third best acoustics in Europe. The main hall has a chandelier made of 3000 kg of bronze. Built in Neo Renaissance style.\nMilan, La Scala opera house\nParis opera house\nBudapest\ntwo statues of greatest composers on two sides of main entrance. Ferenc Erkel (on the left), Ferenc Liszt (on the right), airport is named after second one.\n\n**The House of Terror Museum**\n\n[IMAGE:Terror]\n\nThe House of Terror Museum is a museum dedicated to the victims of 20th-century dictatorships in Budapest, located in a very symbolic location at Andrássy út 60, next to the Oktogon. It was headquartered of the Arrow Cross Militia during WW2, after the war it became a headquarter of Soviet Secret Service. It contains exhibitions related to the fascist and communist regimes in Hungary over the centuries, and commemorates the victims of these regimes, including those who were imprisoned, interrogated, tortured or killed in the building.\n\nMuseum was opened in 2002. On top we can see two words „terror” and signs of Arrow Cross Militia and sign of Soviet Secret Service. In front of the building there is an illustration of „iron curtain” that was between USSR and US. And there is a piece of Berlins wall.\n\n**Andrássy Avenue**\n\n[IMAGE:Andrassy]\n\nAndrássy Avenue is the main road of Budapest. This main road can also be called the Hungarian Champs-Élysées. The main road is bisected by Oktogon Square. The road connects Deák Ferenc Square and the City Park. It is 2.3 km long. The famous M1 metro runs under the square. Many famous buildings can be found on this road, such as the Opera House, the House of Terror, the Kodály Circle, Heroes' Square and the City Park. Sometimes we call it a luxury shopping street, because there are brand shops like Gucci, LV, etc. etc. Also, on this street embassies of different countries can be found.\n\n**The M1 metro line**\n\n[IMAGE:M1]\n\nMetro line M1(the millennial metro) the first metro line in Budapest, running between the Vörösmarty Square and Mexikói Road stations, and runs for the most part under Andrássy út. When it opened in 1896, it was the first underground railway line in continental Europe. The idea and implementation of the underground railway construction are as old as the birth of the London Underground. Its construction began in 1860, and the first underground railway was put into operation in 1863, however, it was still steam-powered. The Budapest Millennium Underground Railway was opened to the public on 2 May 1896 and continues to operate without major disruptions. Until 1973, the length of the line was 3,700 metres, with 9 underground and 2 surface stops. Trains ran every 2 minutes, and the highest daily passenger count was 34,526. Further development did not continue until the end of World War II. According to the customs of the time, the underground railway had left-hand traffic.\n\n",
